By default, we can only really guess the node selector (the bit of the configuration that says how many and of which kind of GPU) for LLMs, otherwise you'll have to specify it in the chute code.  You can view the "Source" tab for any chute to get an idea which node selectors are used for varying chutes.
The standard LLM template chutes have a pricing multiplier that goes by the "cheapest" GPUs that can work (via the node selector) to give you a price per million tokens like the industry standard.  Likewise, diffusion models go by the number of steps in the image generation. The other chutes (anything custom/not templated) is charged by fractional seconds based on the GPU pricing:
https://api.chutes.ai/pricing

The question is, what value do the various scoring feature weights try to ensure exists on the subnet, i.e. which features create the best user experience.
The two big user experience questions are: is a model ready to use, and does it work well?
Unique chute score and bounties incentivize the first part of the question (keeping chutes hot and rewarding cold starts).
Invocation counts and compute units incentivize the latter.
If we look at usage, however, the vast majority of usage is for a handful of chutes; the top 10 chutes account for 94% of usage.
